<Document>
<name>Causeway Coastal Route</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Causeway Coastal Route</h2><p><i>Northern Ireland · Antrim Coast Road, Belfast to Derry/Londonderry</i></p><p><b>200 km of cliff-clinging coast road, basalt sea cliffs, the world's oldest licensed distillery, and Game of Thrones location after location.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>161 km (100 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 2 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–September (June for long light)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Wet roads; tour-coach pull-offs at the Giant's Causeway and Carrick-a-Rede; narrow village high streets</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>267</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Antrim Coast Road from Larne to Cushendall (early 1800s) was one of the great works of British civil engineering, blasting a shelf along the cliff base where boat had been the only previous transport. It links a string of Glens of Antrim villages, a basalt landscape that looks like nowhere else on Earth (the Giant's Causeway), the world's oldest licensed whiskey distillery (Bushmills, 1608), and walled Derry — the only completely walled city in Ireland. Game of Thrones used 30+ filming locations here; the Dark Hedges (a beech tunnel just inland) became the Kingsroad.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Carrickfergus Castle</b> — 12th-century Norman castle on a basalt outcrop above Belfast Lough. King William III landed here in 1690 on the way to the Battle of the Boyne.</li><li><b>Carrick-a-Rede rope bridge</b> — 30 m rope bridge swung between the mainland and a sea-stack — used by salmon fishermen for 350 years; now a National Trust crowd-pleaser. Booking required.</li><li><b>Giant's Causeway</b> — 40,000 hexagonal basalt columns, formed 60 million years ago by cooling lava. Geologically: cooling cracks. Mythologically: built by Finn McCool to walk to Scotland to fight Benandonner.</li><li><b>Old Bushmills Distillery</b> — Granted its license to distill in 1608 by James I — making it the world's oldest licensed whiskey distillery. Tours daily.</li><li><b>Mussenden Temple</b> — Tiny 1785 rotunda perched on a 30 m basalt cliff above the Atlantic. Originally built as the Bishop of Derry's library.</li><li><b>Derry city walls</b> — Built 1613–18, never breached — the only complete city walls in Ireland. Walk the full 1.5 km circuit. The Bogside murals just below recall the Troubles.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
